## ABSTRACT
The growing complexity and speed of modern cyberattacks now exceed the capacity of static rules and manual triage. Organizations are therefore exploring autonomous cyber defense systems capable of interpreting events, deciding, acting, and learning with minimal human intervention. Agentic Artificial Intelligence (agentic AI) provides the theoretical basis for such systems, enabling goal-directed reasoning, sequential planning, and adaptive policy refinement. This essay investigates a Java-based agentic AI architecture for self-learning threat detection, response, and policy adaptation. Drawing on contemporary work by IBM, Microsoft, and Oracle, and on academic research on reinforcement learning, it examines a layered design comprising an event interpretation layer, an autonomous decision layer, and a policy adaptation layer. Java’s concurrency model, strong security libraries, and increasing AI support (e.g., Java 25 enhancements) are analyzed as enabling technologies. A lightweight Java prototype illustrates agents that interpret events, choose defensive actions, and adjust internal policies using reward feedback. The essay concludes with technical and ethical considerations and directions for future Java-based autonomous defense research.







